ce:section.ce:para:
IFE occurs upon the absorption of emitted light by the absorber. Thus, the efficiency of IFE relies on the spectral overlap between the emitter and absorber. In order to explain the pH-dependent effect of FITC on CDs, the spectral overlaps between the emission spectra of CDs and the UV–vis absorption spectra of FITC at different pH values were studied. With increasing pH, the fluorescence spectra of CDs were almost the same, while the fluorescence and UV–vis absorption spectra of FITC changed obviously (Fig. 8
                           ). These results implied the pH-dependence of the spectral overlaps between the emission spectra of CDs and the UV–vis absorption spectra of FITC. From the normalized spectral overlaps between emission spectra of CDs and UV–vis absorption spectra of FITC (Fig. 9
                           ), the area of spectral overlaps was observed to decrease with increasing pH. Due to the largest overlap area at pH5.1, its efficiency of IFE was higher than that at pH7.0 or 9.0. In addition, the overlap area at pH7.0 was a little bit larger than that at pH9.0, leading to a slightly higher IFE efficiency at pH7.0. The results indicated that the IFE efficiency of CDs by FITC was pH-dependent.
